1 Section 1. (Deleted by amendment.)
2 Sec. 2. NRS 62C.230 is hereby amended to read as follows:
3 62C.230 1. If the district attorney files a petition with the
4 juvenile court, the juvenile court may:
5 (a) [Dismiss] Except as otherwise provided in subsection 4,
6 dismiss the petition without prejudice and refer the child to the
7 probation officer for informal supervision [pursuant to NRS
8 62C.200;] if the child voluntarily admits participation in the acts
9 alleged in the petition and if:
10 (1) All parties agree to informal supervision; or
11 (2) The juvenile court finds, after a hearing on the matter,
12 that informal supervision is appropriate; or
13 (b) Place the child under the supervision of the juvenile court
14 pursuant to a supervision and consent decree, without a formal
15 adjudication of delinquency, if the juvenile court receives:
16 (1) The recommendation of the probation officer;
17 (2) The written approval of the district attorney; and
18 (3) The written consent and approval of the child and the
19 parent or guardian of the child.
20 2. If a child is placed under the supervision of the juvenile
21 court pursuant to a supervision and consent decree, the juvenile
22 court may dismiss the petition if the child successfully completes
23 the terms and conditions of the supervision and consent decree.
24 3. If the petition is dismissed pursuant to subsection 2:
25 (a) The child may respond to any inquiry concerning the
26 proceedings and events which brought about the proceedings as if
27 they had not occurred; and
28 (b) The records concerning a supervision and consent decree
29 may be considered in a subsequent proceeding before the juvenile
30 court regarding that child.
31 4. The juvenile court may not refer a child to a probation
32 officer for informal supervision pursuant to paragraph (a) of
33 subsection 1 if the petition filed against the child contains
34 allegations that the child committed an unlawful act which, if
35 committed by an adult, would have constituted:
36 (a) A category A felony; or
37 (b) Any other felony involving the use or threatened use of
38 force or violence.
